        <p class="algo-para">Diffie-Hellman (DH) is a <strong>key agreement protocol</strong> that allows two parties to establish a shared secret over an insecure public channel — without ever transmitting the secret itself. It was the first practical public-key cryptographic protocol, published in 1976.</p>
        <p class="algo-para">DH relies on the <strong>Discrete Logarithm Problem</strong>: given g, p, and gˣ mod p, it is computationally hard to find x. This asymmetry enables the protocol's security.</p>
